<h2>What it does</h2>

<p>
  Ontologyzer is an enterprise data platform inspired by Palantir's ontology approach. It gives organizations a single place to define, connect, and access all their data &mdash; regardless of where it lives or what format it's in. Instead of each team managing data their own way, Ontologyzer provides a unified semantic layer that everyone shares.
</p>

<hr />

<h2>Core capabilities</h2>

<div class="feature-block">
  <div class="feature-label">Structure</div>
  <h4>Ontology-driven data modeling</h4>
  <p>
    Define your business objects &mdash; employees, projects, departments, assets, customers &mdash; and the relationships between them in a central schema. Every object type has consistent properties, validation rules, and access policies across the entire organization. No more conflicting definitions across teams.
  </p>
</div>

<div class="feature-block">
  <div class="feature-label">Access</div>
  <h4>Unified data layer</h4>
  <p>
    Once the ontology is defined, all data is accessible through a single, consistent interface. Query, filter, sort, and aggregate any object type without knowing which database it lives in or how it was originally structured. One API to reach everything.
  </p>
</div>

<div class="feature-block">
  <div class="feature-label">Intelligence</div>
  <h4>AI-ready infrastructure</h4>
  <p>
    The platform automatically generates tools and APIs from your ontology schema that AI agents can use directly. An AI assistant can understand your company's data structure and answer questions like "list all employees in Engineering" or "which projects are over budget" &mdash; without custom integrations. Supports both local and cloud AI models.
  </p>
</div>

<hr />

<h2>How it works</h2>

<p>
  You describe your world once, and Ontologyzer handles the rest:
</p>

<ol>
  <li><strong>Define your ontology:</strong> Declare object types (Employee, Department, Project), their properties, and how they relate to each other (manages, belongs-to, depends-on).</li>
  <li><strong>Connect your sources:</strong> Map data from existing databases, APIs, and external platforms into the ontology. The platform pulls from wherever your data already lives.</li>
  <li><strong>Access uniformly:</strong> Every team, application, and AI agent interacts with data through the same semantic layer &mdash; consistent definitions, consistent access, consistent security.</li>
</ol>

<hr />

<h2>Key features</h2>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Multi-tenant isolation:</strong> Each organization gets fully isolated data and schemas, ready for SaaS deployment</li>
  <li><strong>Fine-grained security:</strong> Row-level, column-level, and action-level access controls that enforce data governance without slowing teams down</li>
  <li><strong>Real-time sync:</strong> Changes propagate across the system in real time through event streaming</li>
  <li><strong>Custom logic:</strong> Define business rules, computed fields, and workflow automations directly within the ontology</li>
  <li><strong>Full-text search:</strong> All data is indexed and searchable out of the box</li>
</ul>

<hr />

<h2>Built for</h2>

<ul>
  <li>Enterprises with data scattered across dozens of systems and no unified view</li>
  <li>Organizations that need strict data governance without sacrificing accessibility</li>
  <li>Teams building AI-powered applications that need structured, reliable data access</li>
  <li>Any company where "which database has the source of truth?" is a recurring question</li>
</ul>

